	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><i><b>In the Name of the Father</b></i> is a 1994 <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biographical_film" title="Biographical film">biographical film</a> directed by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Sheridan" title="Jim Sheridan">Jim Sheridan</a>. It is based on the true life story of the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guildford_Four_and_Maguire_Seven#Guildford_Four" title="Guildford Four and Maguire Seven">Guildford Four</a>, four people <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miscarriage_of_justice" title="Miscarriage of justice">falsely convicted</a> of the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provisional_IRA" title="Provisional IRA">IRA</a>'s <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guildford_pub_bombings" title="Guildford pub bombings">Guildford pub bombings</a> which killed four off-duty British soldiers and a civilian. The screenplay was adapted by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_George" title="Terry George">Terry George</a> and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Sheridan" title="Jim Sheridan">Jim Sheridan</a> from the autobiography <i>Proved Innocent: The Story of Gerry Conlon of the Guildford Four</i> by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guildford_Four_and_Maguire_Seven#Guildford_Four.23Gerry_Conlon" title="Guildford Four and Maguire Seven">Gerry Conlon</a>.</p>
	<h2 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"> <span class="mw-headline" id="Plot">Plot</span></h2>
	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Gerry Conlon is a small time thief living during <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Troubles" title="The Troubles">The Troubles</a> in Belfast, Northern Ireland. After several run-ins with the IRA, Conlon is sent to London to live with his aunt, Anne Maguire, when his father, Giuseppe, is concerned for his safety. While there, he meets with old friends Paul Hill, Patrick Armstrong and Carole Richardson and are seen living life as free hippies as the bombings England begin to escalate, much to their concern. After spending the night on a park bench, where they meet a fellow Irishman named Charlie Burke, Conlon and Hill come across the keys to a prostitute's apartment and decide to rob her for money. After buying the same clothes, Conlon departs and returns to Belfast to his family. During the robbery, the Guildford pub is blown up by the IRA, killing four soldiers and a civilian.</p>
      </wiki:abstract>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">During this time, the sick Guiseppe had been receiving visits from the lawyer <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gareth_Peirce" title="Gareth Peirce">Gareth Peirce</a> who aims to find out the truth and possibly get Guiseppe released of his 12 year sentence on grounds of compassion. Guiseppe dies before this can happen and, although mistrustful of "English lawyers", Conlon decides to dedicate his time in working towards his freedom like his father, along with Peirce. Peirce eventually discovers Charlie Burke's bench as written in Conlon's statement and sneaks into the Police records department to find proof of the cover up and how notes were lying around for the evidence not to be shown to the defence. On the re-trial, the discovery of the lies resulted in the convictions for the Guilford Four being reversed and they all were free to leave the court as they pleased. Outside, Conlon tells reporters of how his father died an innocent man in prison and proclaimed that he would dedicate himself to clearing his father's name.</p>
